  "mechanism_summary": {
    "role_of_KOL": "Acts as surfactant, reduces surface tension, creates stable suspension. Hydrolyzes to produce OH⁻, making the system alkaline (pH ~10). Alkaline environment reacts with SiO₂ to form silicate insoluble substances (softened layer), enhancing chemical removal.",
    "role_of_CeO2": "Ce⁴⁺ can reduce to Ce³⁺. Ce³⁺ reacts with Si-O bonds on the quartz surface, weakening them and forming Ce-O-Si bonds, which are removed under mechanical stress.",
    "role_of_MoS2": "Acts as a solid lubricant due to its layered structure and weak van der Waals forces between layers. Positioned between abrasive, pad, and substrate, it reduces friction and prevents excessive mechanical damage (scratches, pits) caused by hard/irregular CeO₂ particles. Enhances abrasive fluidity and wettability. Does not participate in chemical reactions (confirmed by XPS).",
    "synergistic_effect": "Combination of KOL-induced chemical softening, CeO₂ chemical reactivity (Ce³⁺), and MoS₂ lubrication leads to higher MRR and lower Ra compared to traditional CeO₂ slurry. MoS₂ mitigates mechanical damage while KOL/CeO₂ enhance chemical removal."
  },
